{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_alastor_ver02/data/sn78003992/0034058093A/1958041801/0294.xml":{"full_text":"\"There Is No Need for,\nEmergency Action,\u201d\nPresident Insists :lll:\n800,000 jobs at the start of the spring\nseason. Had the economic decline\neven begun to level off, total employ\nmeat should have risen by a minimum\nof half a million, as it did in previ\nous pre-recession yean.\n\"There is nothing that we in the\nAITLr-ClO would welcome more than\nan end to this recession. But facts are\nfacts and there isn\u2019t a single ray of\nsunshine in today's report.\n\u201cWe can\u2019t see how anyone can take\nencouragement from today's figures,\nparticularly when manufacturers\u2019 or\nders, retail sales, industrial produc\ntion and consumers' income all con\ntinue their steady decline.\n\u201cHe only way to change the situa\ntion is for the government to act now.\nOptimistic press releases won\u2019t end\nthis recession but legislation can,\u201d\nAfeany concluded.\nAsked about Meany\u2019s viewpoint\nEisenhower said Meany was \u201centitled\nto his own opinion.\u201d\nHe himself had \u201conly one recourse,\u2019\u2019\nthe President remarked, and that was\nto get \u201cthe very finest opinions from\nbankers, businessmen and everybody\nI can think of, and I have had the\nlabor group in to give me their views,\nand I think it is just a question where\nwe have to do what we believe best.\u2019\u2019\nHe acknowledged having been dis\nturbed by the fact that living costs go\nup while business declines. But be\n\u201cwent into the history of these de\npressions and found \u201cthat this is not\nan unusual phenomenon; that this\nhas been more, you might say, the\nnormal than abnormal.\u201d\nHis recommendation to the people\nfor combatting the recession was to\n\"buy\u201d almost \u201canything,\u201d but he ob\nserved that maybe the people were\ngetting \"a little bit disenchanted by\na few items that have been chucked\ndown their throats.\u201d\nTreasury Secretary Robert B. An\nderson clearly indicated in a! New\nYork speech that the Administration\nwas more worried about possible fu\nture inflation than about recession\nnow. The government, he said, must\n\"try to avoid those things which\nwould create doubts.\u201d\nThe National Planning Association\nissued statements based on a pro\nfoundly different attitude\u2014the be\nlief that recession: is \u201ccosting\u201d the\nnation 826 billion a year now and that\na failure to end the decline would re\nduce production M0 billion below the\npotential by the end of 1958.\nThe Planning Association, com\nposed of spokesmen of business, agri\nculture and labor, urged \u201clong-range\u201d\nWANTS SENATE ACTION\nON WELFARE FUNDS\nspeedy Senate action on the Doug\nlaa-Kennedy-Ives bill to protect the\npension and welfare money of millions\nof workers has been urged by AFL\nCIO President George Meany.\nIn a letter to Senate Democratic\nLeader Lyndon Johnson (Tex.),\nMeany pointed oat that the benefits\nInvolved In these plans now are \u201cex\ntremely large,\u201d that workers \u201crely on\nthese funds for security In their later\nyears,\" and that prompt congres\nsional action to protect the money Is\n\u201cvital and necessary.\"\nThe bill has been reported favor\nable by an overwhelming majority of\nthe Senate Labor and Public Welfare\nCommittee, the AFLr-CIO president\nnoted, and he aaked Johnson as Sen\nate majority leader to schedule the\nbill for floor action \u201cas soon as pos\nsible.\u201d\nJohnson promptly replied with an\nIndication of a green light for the\nmeasure.\n\u201cI believe,\u201d he wrote Meany, \u201cthat\nthis measure should be passed with\nout crippling amendments and cer\ntainly I will do what I can to achieve\nthat objective.\"\nThe Douglas-Kennedy-Ives bill\nwould require the administrators of\nall largo employe welfare and pen\nsion plans to file with the federal\ngovernment financial reports disclos\ning their stewardship. It would also\nmake false statements and embexzle\nment of the funds Involved federal\ncriminal offenses.\nMeany observed that welfare-plan\nadministration bad been thoroughly\ninvestigated by Senate subcommittees\nheaded In 1854-50 by Senator Paul\nH. Douglas (D-DL), and Senator\nIrving M. Ives (R-N. Y.) and that\nlegislative remedies to correct abuses\nhad been the subject of hearings\nI-by a subcommittee of which Senator\nJohn F. Kennedy, (D-Maas.) was\nchikup.\ntfce Douglas-Ires investigations re\nearned some abuses in the maaago\namt of wulfaxo-sad-penalon money\nend Manny's latter to Johnson said:\n'\"\u2019V:.\n\u2022St\nprogram* for potting the jobless beck\nto work and immediate tax cote to\nexpand purchasing power \u201cim\nprove the tax system.\u201d fox redaction,\nthe NPA said, should eUmfaiato busi\nqesg-burdening excise levies and\nslash individual income taxes \u201cespeci\nally in the lower income brackets.'\u2019\nAhead of Congress, as It returned,\nwas a presumed effort to overturn\nEisenhower\u2019s veto of the farm bill\nthat would have frozen {nice supports\nat existing levels for one year.\nAn attempt to override the veto\nhad to be originated in the Senate and\nleaders did not anticipate they could\nobtain the necessary two-thirds\nmargin.\nSenate Democratic leaders intended\nto take up promptly the Fulbright\ncommunity faculties bill that would\nauthorize $1 billion in federal loans\nfor state and city public works. This\nmeasure, already approved by the\nSenate Banking Committee, was de\nlayed when Republican Floor Leader\nWilliam F. Knowland (Calif.) suc\ncessfully led a drive to postpone con\nsideration until after the recess.\nAlso set for early floor action In\nthe Senate was a compromise Doug\nlas-Payne area redevelopment Mil to\nauthorize major federal aid tot com\nmunities suffering severe and chronic\nunemployment.\nThe Senate passed a similar bill\nin 19S6 but Administration opposition\nprevented its consideration on the\nHouse floor.\nThe basic bill to expand coverage\nof the wage-hour law was still tied\nup in Senate Labor Committee, where\nthe opposition of one Democrat, Sen\nator Strom Thurmond (S. C.,) and\nfailure of any of six Republicans to\nindicate support of the compromise\nmeasure sponsored by Senator John\nF. Kennedy (D-Mass.) has atalmated\naction.\nKennedy's bill would give federal\nminimum-wage protection to about\n6 million workers now not covered.\nThe AFL-CIO endorsed a bill by Sen\nator Wayne Morse (D-Qre.) to cover\n9.6 million workers, but Labor Secre\ntary James P. Mitchell refused to en\ndorse any measure going beyond the\nAdministration proposal to add 2.5\nmillion workers and to deny these\nworkers overtime pay beyound 40\nhours a week.\nThe House, which under the Con\nstitution must originate all revenue\nmeasures, is still tied up by Agree\nment between the Democratic leaders\nand the Administration to give ad\nvance notice of any proposals for tax\nreduction.\n\u201cWhile the great majority entrust\ned with the responsibility for admin\nistration axe honest men, we recog\nnize the temptations now present. By\nplacing these funds, whether run un\nilaterally or jointly by labor and\nmanagement, in a goldfish bowl\nwhere all operations take place before\nthe public gaze, temptations would\nbe removed,\u201d\nThe AFL-CIO has repeatedly asked\nCongress, in 1984 before merger of\nthe two groups and since then as the\nunited labor federation, for disclosure\nlegislation, Meany said.\nThe Eisenhower Administration\nalso has endorsed the \u201ctotal disclos\nure\u201d principle of the Douglas-Ken\nnedy-Ives bill, he continued, and sup\nport is how \u201cbipartisan.\u201d\nThe \u201conly opposition comes from\nsome employer groups and insurance\nspokesmen\u201d and personally, he said,\n\u201cI find this opposition to honest ad\nministration of the funds completely\nIncomprehensible.\u201d\nThe sums involved in welfare and\npension plans, Meany urged, \u201cactually\nrepresent deferred wages\" for the\nworkers covered. The Douglaa-Ken\nnedy-Ives bill would not Impose fed\neral regulation of management of\nthe money but Its requirement for\ncomplete public disclosure of opera\ntions, backed by penal sanctions\nagainst false reports, would power\nfully stimulate honest' and prudent\nadministration, the theory runs.\njobless Fund\n(Continued from Page One)\nTtotal payments made in the last 9\nmonths were 1105,468,028, as com\npared with only 148,089,037 for the\nsame period last year. This boost of\n467,876,968, or 119 per cent, ac\ncounts for nearly all of the total drain\nct 867,623,848 on the fund balance\nduring the year ending March 31,\n1966.: u J.\nUnion Show\n(Continued from Page One)\nvision set. Additional awards to be\nmade by this union include appliances\nof all kinds, a color television set,\nportable TV\u2019s, radios, and various\nsouvenir items.\nThe Stove Mounters\u2019 display will\nfeature the handiwork of that or\nganization\u2019s members in the form\nof stoves\u2014both gas and electric\u2014\nactually In operation with the items\nprepared an them being given to\nthose in attendance.\nTwenty of these ranges will be\ngiven away as prizes, along with\ncharcoal braziers, humidifiers, water\nheaters, window fans and other itefos\nthat depict the crafts and skills of\nthis AFL-CIO union.\nThe Amalgamated Meat Cutters\nand Butcher Workmen\u2019s exhibit\u2014one\nof the largest single exhibits in the\nshow\u2014includes a stage production\nbuilt around the old-fashioned meat\nmarket of yesterday as compared to\nmodem facilities. Tons of union meat\nand related products will be given to\nthose visiting the exhibit.\nTop prizes will be two live, regis\ntered Black Angus steers. Dally\ndemonstrations of sheep shearing,\nconducted by champions In the craft,\nalso will be held.\nOther prizes Include: live ponies,\ncakes, candles and goodies of all\ndescriptions, clothing, soft drinks,\njewelry, groceries, furniture, color\nprints, a fiberglass boat and free\nhaircuts and manicures.\nJoseph Lewis, director of the event\nand secretary-treasurer of the spon\nsoring department, says the show\u2019s\npurpose- is primarily to stimulate\ngreater demand for goods and serv\nices produced by AFL-CIO members,\nand especially those products and\nservices identified by union labels,\nshop cards and service buttons.\n\"The AFL-CIO Union Label and\nService Trades Dept.,\u2019\u2019 Lewis said,\n\u201cconducts year-round campaigns and\nprograms designed to influence and\nguide the buying habits of union\nmembers, their families and the gen\neral public. This annual show is the\ndepartment\u2019s, and the entire labor\nmovement\u2019s, strongest public effort\nfor the accomplishment of this mis\nsion.\u2019\u2019\nHurts World\n(Continued from Page One)'\nexchange reserves are now low except\nIn West Germany.\nThe report voiced the opinion that\nthe \"main dynamic Impulse\u201d to ex\npansion In the U. S. economy may\ncome from higher spending by state\nand local governments, with an addi\ntional stimulus possible through high\ner capital exports.\nSo far as Western Europe countries\nare concerned, the ECE said that\nprospects In Great Britain, France\nand Western Germany are for a\ngreater \"tendency toward stagnation\u201d\nthan In the last half of 1957; the\nNetherlands and Scandinavian coup\ntries are likely to show \u201conly a\nmodest expansion\u201d; and In Belgium\nan actual decline in production is\n\u201cnot Improbable.\u201d _\nSay Uniform Sales\nRacket Operating\nIn Akron Area\nThe Better Brndnana Bureau at Ak\nron, Inc. and the Police Department\nhave been investigating a aalea racket\nin uniforma which has victimized at\nleast 14 business places in the Akron\nIn the past two months a woman\nusing several aliases has taken orders\nfor uniforms tan restaurants, beauty\nshops and doctor's offices.\nThe BBB reported that deposits\nwere paid on the orders and in some\ncases, official receipts were Issued\nbearing the names of wen-known uni\nform sales firms, all located in Mew\nYork State.\nUpon contacting these companies,\ncomplainants were advised that the\n\u201corder-taker\u201d wpa a fraudulent rep\nresentative and no orders had been\nreceived. Complaints are still flowing\nin, according to the BBB, which ad\nvises that there is a possibility that\nthe woman is still operating in\narea. 5. m\nA warning has been issued to busi\nness firms who may be contacted by\nthis .individual, advising them to\ncheck with the BBB before placing\norders for uniforms/\nDistrict 1\n(Centtaued from Page One)\nand that only leaves one day in the\nweek and nothing Is done,\u201d he said.\nOther speakers included Joseph W.\nChilds, URW general vice president;\nDesmond Walker, URW general sec\nretary-treasurer John Rooney, Ohio\nCIO Council executive secretary.\nChilds said the unemployment situa\ntion is critical and, including those\non short work weeks, the equivalent\nof 7 million is out of work. Rooney\nblasted the so-called right-to-work\nproposal, calling it a \"phony that\ndoesn\u2019t guarantee anybody a Job, but,\non the contrary, puts your job in\njeopardy.\"\nOther Council1 officers, named for\none-year terms, include:\nMary Wolff, president of Ravenna,\nO. Local 39, who was named treas\nurer; Herbert Wise, Akron Local 6;\nGeorge Medford, Dayton Local 311;\nJoseph Yaria, Beaver Falls, Pa., Lo\ncal 236; Michael McAleer, Pontiac,\nMich. Local 129; Sam Lanza, Buffalo\nLocal 135, and william Dryer, Find\nday, O. Local 207.\nJoe Emmons of Akron, District 1\ndirector is executive secretary of the\nCouncil.\nMrs. W. G. Giesse\nNew \"Mrs. Ohio\"\nMrs. William G. Giesse of Mayfield\nHeights (Cleveland), 34 year old\nmother of three children last week\nwas crowned \u201cMrs. Ohio\u201d by Mrs. C.\nWilliam O\u2019Neill, Ohio\u2019s, first lady,\nafter winning a one and one-half hour\ncook-off at the state \u201cMrs. America\u201d\ncontest in Columbus.\nMrs. James Bilbrey of Toledo was\nrunner-up.\n\"Mrs. Ohio\u201d will go to Fort Lauder\nFCC Members\nAre Rapped\nIn Report\n(Continued from Pace On)\nducting its own investigation into\npossible law violations posed by testi\nmony during the hearings. In addi\ntion, a federal grand Jury is studying\npossible violations growing out of the\ncommission\u2019s award of the now-fam\nour Miami TV Channel 10 to Nation\nal Airlines.\nHarris also said the sabeoaamtttee\nmay look into the Securities and Ex\nchange Commission and the Federal\nPower Commission before returning\nto Its study of the FOC and the way\nit has handled other contested appli\ncations for television licenses.\nThe hearings have already cost\nCommissioner Richard A. Mack his\nJob. He resigned March 3 following\ntestimony that he had accepted loans\nand other favors from a friend who\nwanted favorable FCC action on Na\ntional Airlines, application for the\nChannel 10 license.\nThe report said that long delays in\ndeciding contested cases, which some\ncommissioners in their testimony laid\nto requirements of the law, contri\nbuted to pressures on FCC members\nwhich \"cannot be tolerated.\u201d\nIn 'addition, it was critical of the\npractice of some commissioners of ac\ncepting payment of expenses at radio\nor television industry meetings while\nalso billing the government for per\ndiem allowances, and questioned the\npropriety of \u201cexcessive entertain\nment\u201d provided for commissioners\nand staff members 'by industry rep\nresentatives. It questioned, too, the\ndesirability of \u201cwholesale attendance\"\nby commissioners at industry meet\ntags.\nDr. Bernard Schwartz, New York\nUniversity law professor whose\ncharges against FCC members at the\nstart of the hearings resulted In Ida\nouster as the subcommittee\u2019s counsel,\nsaid the report:' was good as tor aa It\nwent but that it did not go tor enough\nin some respects. On the ABC \"Col\nlege News Conference\u201d television\nprogram, he said that IT cases which\nthe subcommittee has in its files\nshould be \"developed publicly.\u201d\nhi testimony Just prior to the\nEaster recess, former FCC Commis\nsioner Frieda Hennock told the sub\ncommittee what it ought to bo in\nvestigating is the \"life and death con\ntrol\u201d over television exercised by \"the\nthree television networks, American\nTel. A Tel. and all the other monopo\nlistic interests in this field.\u201d\nMiss Hennock served from 1948 to\nJune 30, 19S5. She charged she had\nbeen \"marked for extinction\u201d from the\ncommission because of her opposition\nto the three major broadcasting net\nworks.\ndale, Fla., to compete in the national\n\u201cMrs. America\u201d finals May 1 through\nMay 13. The contest was sponsored\nin this area by the Bast Ohio Gas\nCompany. i\nMore Opposition Builds\nUp Against Proposed\nOhio \u201cR-to-W\u201d Law\n<OMHaW frii Page Oh)\n\u2019-/ir\n\u2022B of the tanks In the country be\nteller or a tank president ab\nsconded with some of the funds,\u201d the\nAssociation added.\nThe Rev. Bruere said that whatever\nthe Intention at the \"right-to-work\u201d\nlaw, \u201cits effect would be to destroy\nthe principles of collective bargain\ning1.\u201d\n\"The avenge employer wants a\ngood and responsible union to deal\nwith, nbt a disorganized melee of\nindividuals and small groups, unable\nto agree among themselves,\u201d he said.\nThe proposed \u201cright-to-work\u201d\namendment also has been condemned\nin recent statements by the Catholic\nBishops of Ohio and RabM Abba H.\nSilver at Hie Temple in Cleveland.\nAttacking a recent report of the\nU. S. Chamber of Commerce on Fair\ntabor. Standards suit extension, Mr.\nSuffridge characterized the Chamber\nstory as a prime example of the bas\nest form of misleading propaganda. A\ncartful reading of the C. of C. report,\nhe said, demonstrates once more the\nextent to which the big business or\nganization will go in distorting basic\ninformation and pulling quotations\nout of context.\nSaid Mr. Suffridge, \u25a0\u2018the Chamber\nquotes statistics Intended to show\nthat hourly pay in retailing has out\nstripped the improvement in produc\ntivity. It states that the increase in\nproductivity la recent y\u00abani has Item':.\n2.6%. This figure to evidently the one1'\ntor all non-manufacturing Industrie*; 1\nOh the other hand specific data sueh'~A\nas the stsitistice provided by-the.\nSupermarket Institute show that pro-\nduotivity in a branch of retailing such\nas supermarkets has gone up in re-\n-cent years by 5% per annpm. Aver-\nage aalee pm* customer transaction,\nsaid the Supermarket Institute, Jump*\ned from $3.64 in 1961 to $4.29 in\n1956.\u201d This, Mr. Suffrage pointed out,\nwas close to 5% a year.\n\"Betallfaig employes\u2019 waged have i\nnot kept pace with this growth- la\nproductivity. The increase in hourly\npay, according to the Chamber\u2019s own\nfigures, was .3%. It is clear,n con-\ntinned the labor leader, \"that the\nretail employe baa been falling be- A\nhind and has made no wage gains in\nrecent yean, despite the distorted\nclaims of the C. of C.\u201d\n\u201cThe IT. S. Chamber of Commerce 4\nseeks to'justify low wages in certain\nretail lines an the grounds that em-\nployee are not as productive,\u201d Mr.\nSuffridge continued. \u201cThey argue that\nthis is .so where the average trans\naction is a smjjll one. Apparently the\nChamber report was referring to J\nvariety stores and similar enterprises.,\nIt is the KCIA\u2019s contention that con\nsiderable evidence exists to explain\nthat the reason for low productivity\nIn these areas is management ineffi\nciency.\"\nChild\nSees Welt From BOTH EYES\nBinocular vision (using both eyes) is essential\nfor good judgment of the distance of on\ncoming cars. Have your child's eyes checked\nbefore the age of four to give both eyes the\nchance to develop normally.\nV CO-OP OPTICAL\nf&c? Oftent**U\n2317 Manchester Road e PL-3-2266\nWHAT IS SECTION 9(e> (3)f V\nSection 9 (c) (3) of Taft-Hartley says,:\n\u201cEmployees on strike who are not entitled to\nreinstatement shall not be eligible to vote.\"\nftWmm\ni i*\nTHE OmULLlTAN STORY\nOn October 18, 1957, a strange election was\nheld in Winchester, Virginia, scene of the Q'Sulli\nvan strike in progress for 18 months.\nThe fate of a local union was being decided. But\noddly, those most concerned with the election's\noutcome\u2014the members of the union involved in\nthe election\u2014-could not vote.\nOnly those brought in to break the union could\nLABOR WANTS LAW CHANGED\nPresident Eisenhower called this sec\ntion x\"union busting\". It means\nstrikers are denied the right to\nvote on the fate of their own union!\nThis was the hatchet used against\nOSullivan strikers. -i\nV; -HUP CHANGE':\nTAPT-HACTLEY\nYou can help do'battle\nagainst this'injustice by\nwriting your Congressman\nnow. Ask him to support\nthe URW request for qn\ninvestigation into the\n'O'Sullivan strike. *'1 V\nsMj. fc\u2018-v-*rA","height":"25748","width":"20208"}}
